üèÅ The Race is On! üèÅ
‚ùìHave you filled out your 2020 Census? Visit 2020census.gov to learn more!
We're in the final lap of our Race to 100 in the 2020 Census.
üéâThe Snowflake Lobos are in the lead with a 52.4% census response rate.
Holbrook Roadrunners are right behind at 51.8%. #soclose Winslow Bulldogs are in third at 50.6%. Taylor, AZ comes in with 49.1%. Show Low Cougars are at 40.5%, Joseph City Wildcats are at 38%, Pinetop-Lakeside and their Blueridge Yellowjackets are at 32.9%, Heber/Overgaard and their Mogollon Mustangs are at 22.8%.
Our tribal lands are each counted as a whole, and we've assigned their mascots based on prominent mascots in our county.
The Navajo Nation Mustangs have a census response rate of 17.9%, The Hopi Bruins are at 15.7%, and the Ft. Apache Falcons are at 7%.
üèÖThough they aren't in first place, the Ft. Apache Falcons had the biggest gain this week: 2.2% Way to move!
üìàWe will calculate the race weekly and announce the reigning champion each week!

https://www.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=3555746474445188&substory_index=0&id=182956238390912

post_text:
We will be live tonight from the Roost starting at 6 pm!

We are in week 4 of our Phase I Back to School Plan. Each week we all learn something new together from how to navigate our new online learning platform to how online learning workloads differ from when we are in regular classes to ways we can make virtual learning a new way for our students to have access to coursework.

Our leadership team felt it was time to provide an update on our 12-Point Plan, provide more insight into our online learning platforms and provide an opportunity for parents and students to ask questions about our current plan; as well as, our next steps for HUSD #3.

Thank you all for your kindness, patience and dedication to Helping our Unique Students Develop. Our goal from the onset has been to create a safe, healthy and educational environment for all Roadrunners. We will continue that charge and together we will help our students become who they are capable of becoming.

#roadrunnerspirit

REMINDER about Password Resets!

Last night, August 25th, all 3-5 and 6 at IWE passwords were set to Runner20. This will be a one time password and you will be asked to create a new one. It will need to be at least 8 characters long, have at least one uppercase, one lowercase and one number. It cannot have any part of your name.

Password Examples:

HappyDog7! is a bad password, too easy to guess!

h4ppYd0g7! is better, it adds numbers and uppercase

h4Ppd0Gsvn! is best! Not easy to guess but easy to remember

It needs to be easy to remember but hard to guess.

Be internet awesome!

#roadrunnerspirit

IllumiNative
July 30 at 4:21 PM ¬∑

This morning NASA‚Äôs Mars 2020 Perseverance rover launched to explore Mars‚Äô geology and search for signs of life.

NASA Engineer, Aaron Yazzie (Dine') has been working on this project for the last 4 years. The rover will take about 7 months to get to Mars landing on Feb. 18, 2021 in Jezero Crater.

‚ÄúI hope that this mission serves as a symbol to more people than just us, that you can push through. You can persevere.‚Äù - Aaron Yazzie

NASA hopes to launch the pickup mission in 2026 and get the samples back on Earth by 2031 ‚Äî at the soonest.

Learn more about Aaron and other contemporary Native Americans doing incredible things here: https://illuminatives.org/nefa/

A lot happens on the internet; work, education, entertainment, gaming, research, shopping, dating, reunions, stalking, cat-fishing, cyber-bullying, hacking, stealing, black-market dealing, cheating..

Sorry, that took a quick turn. We are already getting reports of cyber-bullying among our Roadrunner students and the improper use of tools like Google Meet outside of class time.

BeInternetAwesome is a site that has a TON of resources from lesson plans to coloring books, to interactive game-quizzes that can help parents and families

https://beinternetawesome.withgoogle.com/en_us/families

post_text:
Have you seen some of our buses out on the roads this week? Traditionally the week before school starts we bring 9 month staff in, like bus drivers, for training and re-acclimation. Though buses wont run like normal on Monday we still needed to bring drivers in for mandatory training. Driving a 45 foot school bus feels a bit different from your sedan or mini-van. You may see more buses on the road next week - please be assured that NO STUDENTS are on campus before August 17th. Your student did not miss the bus and there are no opportunities being afforded some that are not available to all. Once the mandatory training is completed our bus drivers will be incorporated into other operations of the district until they are able to pick up students and bring them to campus.

#RoadrunnerSpirit #TheDrivingForceBehindOurSuccess #BusDrivers

Junior High Families:

Welcome to the 2020-2021 School Year. We are excited to get started. On Thursday and Friday (July 30th/31st) one of the Junior High Teachers will be reaching out. This will be your child's Homeroom Teacher and/or Success Coach. They will walk you through what you can expect when starting in Distance Learning on August 3rd. In addition, they will supply you with login information for your child to connect with their teachers.

If you have not completed registration or scheduled a Chromebook Pick-Up please contact the Junior High Office at 928-524-3959 to schedule an appointment.

We look forward to connecting with you and we are excited to get the new school year started!

Holbrook Unified School District is currently accepting applications for Business Manager.

This executive level position requires a Bachelor's or Master's Degree in accounting or business administration with a minimum of five years of experience.

This position is on a 249 day contract with paid leave, paid medical insurance, and other generous benefit options. The salary range is between $60,500 and $77,445 depending on experience. Additional compensation opportunities exist for capable and well-qualified applicants.

Learn more and apply online at www.holbrook.k12.az.us

Teachers and nine month staff returned to work yesterday and we kicked off the year like we do every year with a keynote speaker. This year was unique in that we did the keynote virtually with Dr. Joe Sanfelippo addressing us from his office in Wisconsin.

Dr. Sanfelippo helped us kick-off our 2020-21 theme "#RoadrunnerSpirit" by sharing his experience in owning and shaping the social media narrative for his school district and the impact that has had on his community.

We invite students, staff, alumni, community members, etc. to use the #RoadrunnerSpirit hashtag to share with one another the wonderful things happening in Holbrook and within our school systems.

We know this year will be unlike any other - but nothing can stop our #RoadrunnerSpirit and our mission to Help Unique Students Develop (HUSD)!

post_text:
A parent recently shared the following story regarding the impact our Substitute Teachers have on students.

"While driving home from a short trip Johnny Cash's "Ring of Fire" came on the radio and my 8 year old son started to sing along exclaiming that he loved this song because Mr. Goodman would sing it to us in class. Another of my children said "Mr. Goodman is my favorite teacher!". Another said "Mine is Mr. Bob." I asked who that was and they said "he's another substitute but he has a hard name so we call him Mr. Bob (Mr. Silverstein). He calls all the boys in class Bob and all the girls Bobbie because he can't remember our names either! So we just call him Mr. Bob.""

Our students love their teachers and don't like to see them out of the classroom however we have some of the most incredible substitutes who step in when needed - often times on a moment's notice.

If you are interested in becoming a substitute teacher you can apply online at: https://holbrook.tedk12.com/hire/index.aspx

We will be broadcasting live from Facebook today at 4:00PM with a Governing Board Work Session to discuss school re-opening procedures including the "12-Point Back to School Plan" drafted by district administrators and school task force committees. We will be fielding questions and taking comments during this work session through Facebook.

The Board will be asked to approve the plan as a working draft in a separate meeting scheduled for today at 6:00PM. Those who attend the 6:00PM meeting will be in listen only mode with no opportunity for public comment or questions.

Questions or comments can be submitted here prior to the meeting. Once the 4:00PM meeting begins questions or comments must be submitted via the live stream.

Good Afternoon HUSD#3,

Online Registration for the 2020-2021 school year is going on now!

You will need to access your parent portal to perform online registration. You can access your IC - Parent Portal (found under "Quick Links" on our website) and when logged in select "More" then "Online Registration"

After the initial registration, parents will be able to stream line registration within the portal year-after-year.

You will be asked to upload proof of residency. This is generally a utility bill or lease agreement showing your physical address (no PO BOXES). Please have proof handy for upload during the registration process.

If you have questions or need help accessing your parent portal please reach out to your child's school - we are all more than happy to help!

Parent Portal:
https://azcloud1.infinitecampus.org/campus/portal/parents/holbrook_unified.jsp

They heard of our mission and efforts to serve food and educational materials to as many children within our district boundaries during this pandemic as possible.

"'Ya‚Äôat‚Äôeeh Dr. Koerperich. We feel grateful for having the opportunity to talk with you last week and send masks to you, your bus drivers, food service team, and outreach staff. Orenda Tribe is a group of artisans selling unique pieces of clothing and jewelery with proceeds supporting their mission on the Navajo Nation.

We appreciate this kind gesture and know the masks will be used by many great people serving our unique students!

post_text:
We made the news again!

Human resources are and will remain our greatest investment - payroll makes up approximately 87% of our $23,000,000 budget!

Though buses are not running and our classrooms are empty, our staff have remained engaged in other duties (i.e. bus drivers working in food service), professional development, remote work, or onsite work in isolation. Through the school shut down all employees have remained on payroll and therefore not much of a savings!

We appreciate Matt Horn and AZ Family Channel 3 and CBS5 for telling Holbrook's story and bringing to light the unique challenges of rural schools!

HHS Band Teacher, Sarah Meeks, has been spotlighting seniors each day. Xyrus had some particularly touching and timely advice for all.

üé∂üé∂üé∂üé∑

2020 HHS Band Senior Spotlight - Xyrus Castillo

Instrument: Tenor Sax & Color Guard

Years in Band: 2

Favorite Band Memory: Stopping at Salt River Canyon while heading towards EAC Honor Band ‚ù§

Favorite Thing Mrs. Meeks Always Says: "You're lucky I love you, Xyrus."

Short Term Plans After High School: Survive the Rona and head to Durango for college.

Long Term Plans After High School: Finish College!! Become all that my parents wish to be and most importantly what I want to be. ‚ù§

What have you learned from Band that you will use throughout your life? Although there are things you are not familiar with, hard work and dedication will help you overcome your fears:)))

What advise would you give the underclassmen and upcoming freshmen in Band? DON'T let anything stop you, I'm still getting that diploma despite Covid-19.

We have updated graduation plans with the news that the "Stay at Home Orders" and curfew remain in effect through June 7th on the Navajo Nation. With that news, the student council in consultation with administration met yesterday and it was decided to move the graduation plans up to 10:00AM (AZ time) on May 22nd allowing us to take advantage of cooler weather and get people home in a timely manner. We ask that you remain patient with us as we prepare and plan for this event in light of the ever changing environment we all find ourselves in.

From the office of Lance Phaturos, Principal of Holbrook High School:

Students and parents, thank you for your patience in regards to retrieving personal items from HHS and/or returning HHS property. At this time, we are obtaining materials from the gymnasium and B/C-building lockers and placing them in bags with respective students‚Äô names on them. Those materials will then be organized and placed in the Roost.

Beginning May 26, you may start to make appointments to obtain your personal items and/or drop off HHS property. Please either call HHS (928-524-2815) or email Ms. Dale (vdale@holbrook.k12.az.us) to schedule an appointment. Please also communicate related information (i.e., what personal items you are seeking to regain and/or what HHS property you will be forwarding). On the day and time of your appointment, an HHS official will meet you in the HHS office parking lot to exchange respective materials.

In order to promote a healthy and safe exchange environment, we reinforce the significance of making an appointment.

Good afternoon from the Holbrook Public Schools,

I hope everyone is staying Roadrunner strong and healthy!

I wanted to remind parents and students that food service will begin deliveries of food on Mondays and Thursdays beginning tomorrow, Monday, April 20th. The deliveries will be for three days so there will not be another delivery until Thursday, April 23rd.

In addition, educational materials will be delivered on Thursdays from this point forward as well. Again, educational materials at both the food service pickups and schools will be on Thursdays.

Just wanted to send a reminder. Please be patient with us tomorrow as we deliver meals. We will be delivering close to 9,000 meals so it will take a while for us to drop off all the materials and we may be delayed getting to the next bus stop but we will deliver to every drop off. We are keeping the same drop off times, there just may be a delay getting to the stop. Stay at the stop and until we arrive.

We hope everyone is well and in good spirits!

Please stay healthy and thank you for being Roadrunners!

Good news for our students in Dilkon and surrounding areas!

Thank you NTUA!
shared_text:
Navajo Tribal Utility Authority
April 9 at 7:28 PM ¬∑

Starting Friday April 10th, Choice NTUA Wireless, NTUA, and the Public Service Company of New Mexico will create three free Wi-Fi Hot Spots on the Navajo Nation for students to use from within the safety of their vehicles.

We received numerous messages from customers asking if we could provide a WiFi area for K-12 and college students to complete assignments. It took a little time, but we got it done.

On April 10th, free temporary WiFi will be available at:
¬∑ Chinle NTUA District Office parking lot
¬∑ Dilkon NTUA District Office
¬∑ New NTUA Headquarters in Fort Defiance.

These sites will operate from 9 AM to 3 PM Monday through Friday except on Holidays. We are looking to provide the same for other communities as things progress. More to come. Please share this post. #NavajoOwnedNavajoProud #NavajoUtilities #NavajoStrong #WeAreEssentialTogether

Mask Makers!

If you could spare some masks our food service staff could use some additional washable masks.

As of now we are suggesting the use of masks. Starting Monday we are requiring the use of masks.

We have about 50 employees and volunteers working daily. We'd like more than one mask per person to allow them to be washed between assignments.

Please drop them off to the district office lobby. We will have a table set up in the lobby if you could please drop them off - leave your name and phone number so we thank you!

It's hard to tell a regular day from a holiday right now however Friday, April 10th, 2020 is a regularly scheduled holiday - Good Friday. Though many of our operations are scaled back - ALL- operations will be on holiday this Friday.

With that said, the wonderful people in food service have doubled up their efforts and we will be delivering TWO BREAKFASTS and TWO LUNCHES tomorrow to cover for the Friday holiday.

There will be no delivery on Friday. Have a great weekend. Stay home, stay safe, and stay healthy!

We hope you are planning to join us for one of our virtual parent/student forums tomorrow. There are three scheduled with the first at 1PM for parents of elementary students, the second will be at 2PM for junior high and high school parents, and the third is scheduled for 3PM and will be geared towards students.

post_text: Thank you all for your patience today as we rolled out the food service program. We apologize for anyone we missed. Once we get this down smooth it might be time to go back to school!! The map that was created is not accessible to all and so we made some screen shots that can be viewed, saved, and shared. Starting Wednesday we hope to incorporate some learning materials into our drop-offs (more information to come). Please note we did need to change a couple of times and added or moved some stops. In most cases we moved the deliveries to be better aligned with where people were waiting for us. Thank you again for your patience. Please continue to share our posts so everyone is brought up to speed.

post_text:
Our food service program begins tomorrow. We ask for some patience and feedback as we get this started. We will run the program as planned and make adjustments for the following week as needed. As changes are needed we will communicate them Thursday and Friday the week before.

We are adding a drive-thru only option at the High School. This is for those who wish to not leave their vehicle. The children must still be present. Please avoid using the neighborhood locations if you wish to remain in your vehicle - we don't want to cause a dangerous situation with walk-up and drive-up. The drive-thru hours will be 8:00AM to 8:45AM.

More information can be found at:
http://www.holbrook.k12.az.us/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=6GAUAA0&dasi=3UII

Want to give a BIG shout out to everyone who has helped to pull together our food service program for next week! Just like this was sprung on all of you it was sprung on them and they stepped up and showed they are ALL IN!!

The day started at 6:30AM with the preparation of 1,200 sack breakfasts and 1,200 sack lunches!!

Then we trained drivers on the schedule, routes, and safety expectations.

Then the servers and food distributors joined the training. All will be working this weekend to get their food handler permits online so we are in compliance.

Thank you to everyone who stepped up this week!!!

Please be kind and show some appreciation to these wonderful people who have volunteered to take on additional duties to serve the children of our communities!

The first week will have some growing pains but we are committed to doing our best!

More info on our website at www.holbrook.k12.az.us

Governor Doug Ducey is with Superintendent Kathy Hoffman and Arizona Department of Education.
March 15 at 11:14 PM ¬∑

We‚Äôre joining together to keep Arizona‚Äôs kids, families, and school communities safe and healthy. Arizona is united, and we‚Äôll get through this. Superintendent Kathy Hoffman

This decision is not made lightly, but it is the right thing to do to bring certainty and consistency to all Arizona schools. With schools closing, we are working together to provide assistance during this time and lessen the impact on all Arizona families.

It‚Äôs important for families & parents to know that while this will address operational issues, closing schools will not stop the spread of #COVID19. It is the recommendation of public health officials that kids who are not at school remain at home to the greatest extent possible.

For more information on ways to stay safe and healthy, visit http://azhealth.gov.

Read our full letter here: https://azgovernor.gov/governor/blog/2020/03/open-letter-arizona-families-educators-school-leaders-and-education-community

post_text:
‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è Regarding Valentine's Day Tomorrow ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è

We want to remind parents that balloons, flowers, vases, large stuffed animals, etc. are not permitted on the school buses. Students will not be permitted to board the bus with these items. These are federal guidelines for the safety of all on the bus. We appreciate your support on this.

We also ask and highly encourage you to save elaborate gestures and gift giving for home - either before or after school. Sending or dropping off these gifts at school causes a disruption to the classroom and adds burden to our busy office staff. Many teachers and schools have carved out time to celebrate Valentine's Day so rest assured they will feel the love while at school!!

Some of the elementary classes are inviting students to bring Valentines to share and boxes to collect them in - if your student rides the bus these need to be appropriate in size and shape and preferably fit inside their back pack.

Hopefully there is no love lost with these requests! We thank you in advance for your support!

Tax documents are arriving in the mail and return preparation begins. If you find yourself owing money to the State of Arizona consider making a tax credit donation to one of our many extracurricular programs!

In Arizona your donation to an approved tax-credit extracurricular program can offset your tax liability dollar-for-dollar (up to $200 for an individual and $400 if filing married/jointly).

Donations that apply to your 2019 taxes can be made up until tax filing deadline: April 15, 2020. Visit the District Office at 1001 N 8th Ave for more information or any one of the school offices!

Be sure to talk to your tax adviser and visit our website for more information:

http://www.holbrook.k12.az.us/SchoolTaxCredits.aspx

****Attention Juniors and Seniors and Parents/Guardians of Juniors and Seniors****

Holbrook High School Counselor, Mrs. Warner, is available to help with all your after high school education goals and plans. Whether you are looking to get into a trade school, community college, university, or join the military she is there to help. Everyday, Monday through Friday, she is available in her office during lunch, 5th, and 6th hours (bring a pass if coming 5th or 6th hour). In addition, Mrs. Warner stays late every Thursday evening and is available until 6:15PM. Mrs. Warner can help with applications, essays, FAFSA, grants, scholarships, and more.

No matter where your student is in the planning phase - Mrs. Warner can help! Stop by and see her sooner than later.

#JustDoIt #ALLIN #Roadrunner #GraduationStation #YouCanGetThereFromHere #Classof2020 #Classof2021

The Din√© Institute for Navajo Nation Educators (DIN√â) is a partnership between Northern Arizona University and schools on the Navajo Nation who are participating in the Yale National Initiative. The Institute provides innovative K-12 teacher professional development that elevates curricular rigor and strengthens culturally responsive teaching in public, BIE, and tribally-controlled schools across the Din√© Nation.

Theresa Yazzie and Bernice Gover, both teacher as Indian Wells Elementary School, were selected and have participated in the institute during the last year and will be showcasing their work this Saturday at NAU.

Those wishing to support these two great roadrunner teachers - or wishing to learn more about incorporating Native American culture into K-12 education are invited and encouraged to attend.

RSVP at www.nau.edu/dinersvp

Congratulations and a big thanks to Theresa and Bernice for being leaders in cultural integration at HUSD #3! #ALLIN

Hulet Elementary School was awarded the PBISaz Merit Achievement Award for successful implementation and measurable student outcomes with school-wide systems of Positive Behavior Interventions and Supports (PBIS). Award criteria required high scores on national fidelity and integrity assessments AND measurable student outcome data.

Principal Kevin Fosburgh notes that this award recognizes the dedication of school staff and our community to uphold our school expectations every day: Be Respectful, Responsible, Safe, and Kind. Together we are building a school culture that is more positive, proactive, and supportive for all our students so that they can be successful citizens and leaders of our nation.

post_text:
Hey Roadrunners...You can get there from here!

Holbrook High School Principal, Mr. Phaturos, just took a phone call from a very proud Michelle Thomas, an HHS alumna, who shared with him that she had just won a Native American Music Award (basically the Native American music Grammy!). He stated "I didn't remember her in any of our performing arts programs so I asked her about this and she responded, "No, I wasn't in choir or band, but remember I used to sing the National Anthem at games in Navajo! This is where it started!""

Congratulations Michelle!

Once a Roadrunner, Always a Roadrunner!

When One Roadrunner Succeeds - We ALL Succeed!

Students from Holbrook Junior High School search "Live Laugh Love" Park in Holbrook for hidden treasure!

Holbrook Junior High's Power of All program offers students an hour of tutoring in exchange for an hour of fun activity Wednesday evenings during a 15 week period. The students photographed below attended their first week of tutoring and then were taken to explore Holbrook in search of Geocaches.

Geocaching is a popular past time that requires participants to search for hidden log books and prizes using GPS and clues. Coordinates are posted to www.geocaching.com for anyone to find. There are literally millions hidden worldwide including many in the Holbrook area. It is the worlds largest scavenger hunt!

The Power of All program uses clubs, such as the Geocaching Club, as incentive for studying and improving grades.

#HolbrookJuniorHIgh #Roadrunners #ALLIN #Geocaching #PowerOfAll

post_text:
Join us Saturday at Hunt Park for our first Healthy Holbrook Roadrunner 5K!

We will have a DJ at the start line to get people moving and warmed up. The route purposely doubles back on itself so you are only ever half-a-5K away from your vehicle if you decide it is too much OR you already know you want to participate but can only do 2.5K. We want to accommodate as many as possible.

If you are not up for the run/walk you can volunteer at a water/aid station or just cheer participants on along the route!

Please familiarize yourself with the route below which will also be marked the during the event.

Stick around after for hot chocolate and muffins provided by the District Food Service Department.

This is a free community wellness event sponsored by Holbrook Public Schools, Winslow Indian Health Care Center, and the University of Arizona Cooperative Extension. We also appreciate the City of Holbrook for providing restroom facilities and traffic control.

post_text:
Our next Roost EdTalk will be on November 21, 2019 at 6:30PM in the Roadrunner Roost at Holbrook High School.

We are excited and look forward to hearing from Sergeant Patterson of the Holbrook Police Department who will lead the discussion on "Adolescent Drug & Alcohol Use Trends." As you can imagine Sergeant Patterson, in his capacity, has invaluable experience and expertise to share with parents on what exactly is happening in Holbrook and surrounding areas.

In addition, Sergeant Patterson will share strategies for parents to recognize drug and alcohol use in children and share resources to help parents of children using or exposed to drugs and alcohol.

This is a presentation you won't want to miss!

There is no cost for attendance and light refreshments are provided by the Roadrunner Roost Cafe. Community members are encouraged to network and socialize following the discussion. We hope to see you there.

Bus drivers are the DRIVING FORCE behind our success! They are true ROAD-runners!! They transport nearly 1,000 students a day more than half-a-million miles annually! Bus drivers are the first to greet most of our students in the morning and last to tell them goodbye each school day. Our school bus drivers are some of the first ones to clock-in and the last to clock-out each day. They do their job with pride and with safety at the forefront of their minds.

Please take a moment and thank a bus driver this week for all that they do!

#ALLIN #ROADRUNNERS #BUSDRIVERS

The Holbrook School District in coordination with the City of Holbrook and Navajo County will be hosting our annual Walk With Me to Be Drug Free walk to school day on Tuesday, October 22nd beginning at 7:45 am at the Old Courthouse across from Wells Fargo Bank.

The Holbrook School District will be celebrating Drug Free week next week and into the following week.

As part of the week‚Äôs activities we would like you to join us as we walk to school together as a sign that we are committed to be drug free. We encourage everyone to wear red as a sign of respect for Red Ribbon Week.

All bus students will be dropped off to walk with us to school. If your child normally walks to school or gets dropped off they will need a permission form to ensure we are accountable for them.

If you have additional questions, you may contact your child‚Äôs schools for details.

We hope you can join us next Tuesday at 7:45 am at the Old Courthouse in Holbrook for Walk With Me to Be Drug Free!

post_text:
Holbrook Unified School District takes a "Whole Student" approach to education. In addition to academics, our system focuses on personal and social success. This is most recently evident at our High School where we have implemented the PASS period where students are able to work with teacher mentors on Personal, Academic, and Social goals (similar to the mentoring occurring at HJHS).

One teacher shared with her colleagues a recent success where a student successfully brought her grades up to all A's and B's. When asked about her success at Holbrook High School compared to her prior school the student stated "[the other school] seemed to focus on passing the assessment while HHS focuses on student learning!"

The school you attend and the teachers you work with matter! To students and teachers alike we say "Thank you for choosing HUSD!"

#ALLIN #Roadrunners #HHS

Tonight at 6:00PM we invite parents, guardians, and community members to attend Crisis Reality Training with Jesus Villahermosa. Jesus is a nationally renowned expert on school violence and he is in Holbrook to share his experience and wisdom.

While we certainly hope none in our community experience such an event, the chances are ever increasing. Whether it be in school, church, malls, concert venues, or anywhere else the tactics he will teach could save your life! Two white mountain students attending a softball camp were actually in the El Paso, TX Wal-Mart during the recent tragedy. They had previously attended this same training and credit Jesus Villahermosa for their survival.

Join us in the George Gardner Performing Art Center this evening at 6:00PM. Please also remember that all schools will be closed today at 1PM so staff can attend staff specific training with Jesus.

We'd like to remind parents and guardians of an upcoming safety event occuring in September 20th at the George Gardner Performing Art Center at 6PM.

One concern that was expressed when we embarked on the creation of the Roadrunner Roost at Holbrook High School was "what about the library?! Where are all the books going?!"

We've previously shared that the library was not going away but instead being restructured to meet the many needs of the students.

Our High School Librarian, Mrs. Krista Smith shared:

"Thank you for boosting the popularity of the library. I have enjoyed seeing students come in the library and study and visit in what is obviously a comfortable environment for them."

She ran some figures and reported that when compared to the same time period as last year students have checked out 387 more books this year!

Did you know Holbrook High School has an E-Sports team? Do you know what an E-Sports team is? There are many misconceptions regarding what it is and what it is not.

Our IT Director, Mr. Barry Lambson, discusses E-Sports with Tyler Schrodt, founder of the Electronic Gaming Federation in New York, on a podcast he co-hosts called "Red Barn Podcast." Together they debunk some of the mis-information and discuss the value such a team adds to diversify options available to students especially in rural settings like Northern Arizona.

Give the podcast listen here:

https://www.podomatic.com/podcasts/redbarnpodcast/episodes/2018-06-03T22_14_12-07_00

Join us this Thursday at 6:30PM for our first in a series of talks we're calling RoostEd. These discussion will take place in Holbrook High School's student lounge "Roadrunner Roost" and focus on a variety of topics important to education and our community.

Our first discussion will cover Positive Behavior Intervention Systems (PBIS). These systems are being implemented in schools throughout our district and we'd like to share with parents and guardians some of the science behind PBIS and what can be done at home to foster the same environment. Also, there will be a brief discussion with Dr. Koerperich, Superintendent, on school safety in preparation for a larger safety event happening in September. Lastly, we are highlighting some of the offerings available at the all new Roadrunner Roost Cafe. Enjoy some complementary breads, drinks, and other items while learning and discussing issues important to education and our community.

shared_text:
Holbrook Police Department
August 9, 2019 at 4:47 AM ¬∑

***PUBLIC ANNOUNCEMENT***

Tonight, 08/08/2019 the Holbrook Police Department responded to the Holbrook High School area in reference to a possible fight and shots being fired. Officers responded and located kids playing football at the football field. It was also found out that some fireworks had been shot off. There was no fight that occurred.

The Holbrook Dormitory had been placed on a soft lockdown by staff. After it was determined the "shots" were just fireworks, dorm staff was notified and the soft lockdown was lifted.

It was brought to the attention of the police department that there are facebook post(s) stating there was a shooting at the dorms. This is FALSE and there was no shooting at the dorms or in the area of the high school. Per the dorm staff all students are safe.
